                        VIEW SLIDESHOW
5 photos
                        














































                A rendering of the leisure pool in The Woodlands Hills master-planned community north of… more 








 



The Howard Hughes Corp. has unveiled its latest master-planned community in the Houston area.
The Dallas-based developer (NYSE: HHC) and its wholly-owned subsidiary, The Woodlands Development Co., announced The Woodlands Hills, which will rise on a little more than 2,000 acres in Conroe and Willis.
















                                    VIEW SLIDESHOW
5 photos




















































                A rendering of the leisure pool in The Woodlands Hills master-planned community north of… more 






 


The community, located on FM 830 west of Interstate 45 between League Line Road and FM 1097, is about four miles from Lake Conroe, about 10 miles from Johnson Development Corp.'s Grand Central Park master-planned community on the former Boy Scouts' Camp Strake property and about 13 miles north of The Woodlands. The Howard Hughes Corp. first purchased the property in summer 2014.
The Woodlands Hills — named after the pine-forested hills of the land — is The Howard Hughes Corp.’s third master-planned community in the Houston area after The Woodlands north of Houston and Bridgeland northwest of Houston. The name also gives a nod to The Woodlands, The Howard Hughes Corp.’s flagship master-planned community that is nearing build-out.




“We wanted to capture and extend The Woodlands' vision,” said Heath Melton, Howard Hughes’ vice president of master-planned communities, residential development.
The new community will feature more than 4,500 single-family homes, including homes at a more affordable price point, officials said. The Howard Hughes Corp. plans to announce homebuilders later this summer, but company officials hinted that the community could have as many as eight builders on four separate lot sizes. Home sizes, prices and features also will be announced at a later date.
Community amenities will include 112 acres of green space including 20 neighborhood parks as well as extensive hike and bike trails, including bike lanes on major roads. A 17-acre village park will feature a model home park, a resort-style pool with a lazy river, a play area for children, a fitness center and lap pool for adults, tennis courts, an events lawn with a stage and artificial turf area for outdoor fitness classes such as yoga. A future commercial and retail development is also planned on more than 100 acres within the community.





 


Click through the slideshow to see renderings of The Woodlands Hills’ amenities.
Children living in The Woodlands Hills will be zoned to Willis Independent School District’s Meador Elementary, Brabham Middle and Willis High schools. The school district has land within the community earmarked for a future elementary school.
The Woodlands Hills will likely attract residents working in energy and medical professions in The Woodlands. Millennials and empty-nesters in particular will likely gravitate toward the community, which will offer more value-oriented homes than The Woodlands, said Tim Welbes, co-president of The Woodlands Development Co.
“Millennials are helping to sustain the housing market,” Welbes said. “As older Millennials have children, they want that proximity to work and schools so they can spend more time with family.”
Construction crews are expected to break ground in September on the first five sections of homes within The Woodlands Hills, which will consist of a couple hundred lots, officials said. A grand opening is planned in spring 2018.
Developers are building master-planned communities farther into the exurbs as Houston’s suburban population continues to grow. As The Woodlands nears residential buildout within three years, The Howard Hughes Corp. has staked the next chapter of its north Houston development within Conroe — the fastest-growing city in America, according to the U.S. Census.
Toby Powell, the mayor of Conroe, was born and raised in Conroe. The 76-year-old remembers a time decades ago when his city had a population of just 5,000. Today, Conroe boasts more than 82,000 residents, and the city is expected to have 100,000 residents by 2020, he said. The Woodlands Hills will be one of the largest master-planned communities in Conroe, he added.
“We are excited to have new homes, affordable homes, with great amenities in Conroe,” Powell said.

Paul Takahashi covers residential and multifamily commercial real estate, as well as education, for the Houston Business Journal. Follow him on Twitter for more.









 






