Blog




How Collaborative Software Boosts Performance for Leading National Developer

					Wednesday January 18, 2017					     |     
					By: Ashley Garcia




Share



Tweet



Share



Share



Email




When you think of Howard Hughes, you probably think aviation and movies, not real-estate and construction, right? But the Howard Hughes Corporation is, in fact, a major real estate development and management company based in Dallas, Texas. Founded in the early 1900’s, Howard Hughes Sr. formed the company selling oil well drilling bits. Since then, the company has undergone several transformations to become one of the country’s most preeminent developers.The company’s portfolio is comprised of master planned communities, operating properties, strategic development opportunities and other assets spanning 16 states from Waikiki to Wall Street! Being that the portfolio is so vast, Howard Hughes Corporation (HHC) relies primarily on the construction management-at-risk (CMAR) project delivery method and some integrated project delivery (IPD) philosophies embedded into the processes.CMAR – A delivery method which entails a commitment by the Construction Manager (CM) to deliver the project within a Guaranteed Maximum Price (GMP) which is based on the construction documents and specifications at the time of the GMP plus any reasonably inferred items or tasks. 1IPD – A Collaborative alliance of people, systems, business structures and practices into a process that harnesses the talents and insights of all participants to optimize projects results, increase value to the owner, reduce waste, and maximize efficiency through all phases of design, fabrication, and construction.2The Preconstruction and Construction Management department are responsible for establishing corporate construction standards and project oversight, essentially acting as an owner’s rep between headquarters in Dallas and the regional offices throughout the U.S. Following the CMAR methodology allows the Preconstruction and Construction Management department to essentially act as a consultant to the owner in the design development and construction phases – ultimately managing and controlling the construction costs to not exceed the GMP. This methodology provides a very high level of cost control from the start – which is why Howard Hughes needed a system in place to provide full transparency and accountability on all projects.Read the case study to learn more about how the Howard Hughes Corporation is utilizing e-Builder Enterprise to integrate with their financial system, provide visibility across all projects, and has become the “collaborative backbone for success.”Sources: 1. https://www.ccgov.net/DocumentCenter/View/3238 2. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integrated_project_delivery 



